# TypeScript & Code Quality Standards

## TypeScript Configuration
- **Config**: [tsconfig.json](mdc:tsconfig.json) with strict mode enabled
- **Path Mapping**: `@/*` maps to `./src/*` for absolute imports
- **Target**: ES2015 with modern module resolution

## Type Definitions
- **Location**: [src/lib/](mdc:src/lib/) for shared types
- **API Types**: [src/lib/api.types.ts](mdc:src/lib/api.types.ts)
- **Database Types**: [src/lib/database.types.ts](mdc:src/lib/database.types.ts)

## Type Patterns
```tsx
// Interface for component props
interface Props {
  required: string;
  optional?: number;
  children?: ReactNode;
}

// Type for API responses
interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  error?: string;
}

// Generic utility types
type FormData = {
  email: string;
  password: string;
}
```

## Import Standards
- **Absolute Imports**: Use `@/` prefix for internal modules
- **External Libraries**: Standard npm package imports
- **Type Imports**: Use `import type` for type-only imports
- **Example**: `import type { Metadata } from 'next';`

## Code Quality Tools
- **ESLint**: [eslint.config.mjs](mdc:eslint.config.mjs) with Next.js and TypeScript rules
- **Prettier**: Configured for consistent formatting
- **Scripts**: 
  - `pnpm lint` - Check for issues
  - `pnpm lint:fix` - Auto-fix issues
  - `pnpm prettier` - Format code

## Strict TypeScript Rules
- **No Implicit Any**: All variables must have explicit types
- **Strict Null Checks**: Handle undefined/null cases
- **No Unused Variables**: Remove unused imports and variables
- **Explicit Return Types**: For complex functions, prefer explicit return types

## React TypeScript Patterns
```tsx
// Component with props
export function Component({ title, count }: Props) {
  return <div>{title}: {count}</div>;
}

// Server Component (default)
export default async function Page() {
  // Server-side logic
  return <div>Content</div>;
}

// Client Component
'use client';
export function InteractiveComponent() {
  const [state, setState] = useState<string>('');
  // Client-side logic
}
```

## Utility Types Usage
- **ReactNode**: For children props
- **Readonly**: For immutable data structures
- **Partial**: For optional object properties
- **Pick/Omit**: For selective type extraction

## Error Handling Types
```tsx
interface ErrorResponse {
  error: string;
}

// Union types for different outcomes
type Result<T> = T | ErrorResponse;
```